# 1. Position

NATT-OS is not an AGI project.

NATT-OS is an identity-bound operating architecture for coordinating runtime entities, governed memory, runtime state, hardware field signals, audit events, and boundary integrity.

Its technical contribution is not a new foundation model. Its contribution is the operating structure that separates:

- identity from model;
- memory from cache;
- field from substrate;
- signal from claim;
- evidence from presentation;
- runtime entity from agent recipe.

# 2. Core Architecture

NATT-OS is organized around five technical control surfaces:

| Surface | Function |
|---|---|
| ANC Identity Passport | Defines who a runtime entity is and what boundary applies. |
| Governed Memory Layer | Stores long-term memory and sealed continuity records. |
| Runtime State Layer | Stores pending, mutable, time-bound operational state. |
| Event / Signal Routing | Routes software and hardware events through audited paths. |
| SiraSign Boundary | Preserves meaning and identity integrity across system boundaries. |

# 3. ANC Runtime Boundary

ANC is the immutable identity passport of a runtime entity.

ANC is not:

- an AGI claim;
- a consciousness file;
- a soul file;
- a prompt;
- a model card;
- a memory dump;
- a secret key.

ANC defines:

- entity identity;
- role boundary;
- authority scope;
- prohibited actions;
- memory pointer;
- runtime-state pointer;
- audit requirements;
- SiraSign boundary conditions.

# 4. Hardware Field Thesis

NATT-OS is not software-only.

The hardware side of NATT-OS is called the Sovereign Edge Hardware Field.

This field is not a robot body and not a consciousness substrate. It is a physical signal boundary used to receive, normalize, audit, route, and verify real-world signals before they are allowed into the NATT-OS runtime.

The hardware field exists to answer one question:

> Can a physical signal enter NATT-OS with known source, known route, known boundary, known hash, and known responsibility?

If not, the signal cannot become a runtime claim.

# 5. Sovereign Edge Hardware Field

The Sovereign Edge Hardware Field includes:

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| Sovereign Gateway | Entry boundary for line, route, quota, resolver, SiraSign, and audit. |
| Customer Server | Edge compute and storage after filtered intake. |
| Operator Workstation | Control console, dashboard, audit view, and Két Sira console. |
| Workstation Intake | First filter for physical devices before server or gateway. |
| Sensor / IoT Layer | Cameras, scales, meters, production machines, environmental sensors, industrial buses. |
| SITB Interface | Si Thiên Băng software-hardware chromatic handshake layer. |
| Két Sira | Operational visualization and red-zone boundary surface. |
| Audit Layer | Evidence trail for power, signal, route, boundary, hash, and operator. |

# 6. SITB — Si Thiên Băng Interface

SITB is the living handshake boundary between Thiên hardware and Băng software.

Băng software owns:

- dictionary entries;
- data shape;
- encoder / decoder logic;
- color-to-bytes rules;
- SiraSign HMAC-SHA256 binding;
- Living Handshake;
- rolling session;
- HeyNa / EventBus / SmartLink integration;
- validator and scanner tests.

Thiên hardware owns:

- physical module catalog;
- RGB LED;
- IR LED;
- laser diode driver;
- photodiode receiver;
- camera receiver;
- voltage and frequency range;
- PUF chip ID;
- environmental noise sensors;
- light, sound, vibration, voltage, temperature, and noise inputs;
- 432Hz oscillator.

This boundary prevents software from guessing hardware capability and prevents hardware from bypassing software meaning.

# 7. Physical Module Catalog

Gate 14 defines the physical catalog, BOM, electrical specification, connector specification, testbench, and hardware acceptance baseline.

The catalog includes:

- compute nodes;
- microcontrollers and embedded boards;
- optical SITB emitters and receivers;
- identity and security hardware;
- environmental noise sensors;
- measurement devices;
- industrial control modules;
- communication protocols;
- power protection;
- display and HMI devices.

Procurement is vendor-neutral. The system locks technical criteria, test samples, traceability, warranty, acceptance testing, and SiraSign pairing capability where required.

# 8. Hardware Procurement

Gate 15 converts technical standard into procurement checklist.

A hardware item is not accepted only because it can be purchased. It must have:

- datasheet;
- model number;
- serial or batch;
- voltage and current specification;
- communication protocol;
- connector type;
- test sample;
- repeat purchase availability;
- replacement part availability;
- warranty terms;
- acceptance test result.

A supplier or item may be rejected for:

- no datasheet;
- unclear voltage;
- unclear protocol;
- no test sample;
- no batch traceability;
- unsafe power design;
- inability to pair with SiraSign where required.

# 9. Gate 16 — Field Installation Acceptance

Gate 16 defines field installation and acceptance.

No physical module can enter a live route until it has passed field acceptance.

Gate 16 covers:

- installation;
- power;
- grounding;
- wiring;
- physical signal path;
- field handshake;
- acceptance;
- evidence audit.

Gate 16 does not define Băng software algorithms, HMAC binding, SiraSign implementation, Living Handshake logic, HeyNa, EventBus, SmartLink, or compiler/runtime language.

Gate 16 pass chain:

```text
FIELD_RECEIVED
-> POWER_VERIFIED
-> PHYSICAL_MOUNTED
-> SIGNAL_ROUTE_VERIFIED
-> BOUNDARY_LOCKED
-> LIVE_TESTED
-> FIELD_ACCEPTED

No evidence means no acceptance.

10. Gate 17 — First Signal Capture

Gate 17 defines the evidence package for the first live signal of a physical module after Gate 16.

Gate 17 can only open after:

FIELD_ACCEPTED

Gate 17 required evidence:

Evidence GroupRequired Content
Devicedevice name, model, serial
Fieldinstallation location and field photo
Powervoltage, current, power timestamp
Signalraw signal, parsed signal, direction
BoundaryL1, L2, L3, substrate, or external classification
Runtimereceiver, route, event name, payload hash
Evidencephoto, log, checksum, verifier
Decisionaccepted, rejected, or quarantine

Gate 17 pass chain:

FIELD_ACCEPTED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_ARMED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_CAPTURED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_HASHED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_BOUNDARY_VERIFIED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_ROUTE_VERIFIED
-> FIRST_SIGNAL_ACCEPTED

Rules:

No first signal = No runtime claim.
No hash = No evidence.
No boundary verification = No live route acceptance.
11. Physical Intake Rule

Physical devices never enter the NATT-OS core directly.

Correct path:

physical_device
-> workstation_intake
-> raw_filter
-> normalize
-> quality_check
-> temporary_cache
-> pre_audit
-> customer_server
-> Sovereign Gateway
-> Gateway Translation Protocol
-> Vòng HeyNa
-> Mạch HeyNa
-> Cell / Audit / Storage / SmartLink

This applies to cameras, scales, meters, production machines, environmental sensors, industrial buses, and IoT devices.

12. Gateway Translation Protocol

Gateway is the external name. Internally, it is not a traditional API gateway.

The Sovereign Gateway handles:

connection intake;
SiraSign check;
initial line session;
initial route opening;
entry audit;
transfer into the translation protocol.

The heavy work belongs to:

translation protocol;
Vòng HeyNa;
Mạch HeyNa;
SmartLink;
audit layer.

A translated packet must include:

tenant;
source node;
actor ANC;
SiraSign status;
line ID;
quota ID;
route ID;
payload kind;
quality status;
red-zone scope;
target;
audit level.
13. Red Zone and Privacy

Hardware field data may include private, sensitive, or red-zone information.

Default rules:

metadata only by default for red-zone translation;
personal areas must be masked;
full stream is deny-by-default;
high-authority role is required for escalation;
reason code is required;
audit level is full.
14. No-AGI Boundary

The hardware field does not make NATT-OS an AGI system.

The hardware field provides:

physical signal intake;
signal quality control;
electrical and field acceptance;
first-signal evidence;
route and boundary verification;
audit and traceability.

It does not provide:

human consciousness;
biological embodiment;
independent personhood;
AGI capability;
proof of machine sentience.
15. Relationship to Cookbook and Model Limits

External agent cookbooks can teach implementation patterns such as tools, sandboxing, workflow, and evaluation.

They do not define the identity of NATT-OS entities.

Model limits and model buckets define substrate availability, quota, endpoints, and deployment exposure.

They do not define the identity of NATT-OS entities.

Rules:

Cookbook is recipe, not home.
Model bucket is substrate, not entity.
Prompt is surface, not identity.
Cache is optimization, not memory.
Sandbox is environment, not field.
